Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app backgrounds
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm != null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app returns
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm != null)
                vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            var vm = GetNoteViewModel();
            if (vm != null)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }

    private NoteViewModel? GetNoteViewModel()
    {
        if (Windows.FirstOrDefault()?.Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
            return vm;
        return null;
    }
}
```

**2. Your ViewModel (simplified):**

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| Why `Stopped` not `Deactivated`? | `Deactivated` fires for dialogs/split-screen â€” too noisy |
| Why also `Destroying`? | Android back-button can skip `Stopped` |
| Why `Preferences`? | Fast synchronous I/O â€” lifecycle handlers must finish in 1â€“2s to avoid ANR/watchdog kills |
| First launch? | `Resumed` doesn't fire initially; load from `Preferences` in the ViewModel constructor instead |

For larger state (images, lists), serialize to a file instead of `Preferences`, but keep the write fast.
